We've read data in and transformed it. Now we have to write it back out, and this is the mirror image of the read side. The entry point is df dot write, and just like reading, a handful of knobs control exactly what happens and where the data lands.

Let's start with format, how the data gets encoded on the way out. Parquet should be your default. It's columnar, compressed, and keeps your types, so whoever reads it next gets a fast, self-describing dataset. CSV is there when some other tool demands plain text, but you lose types and compression. JSON for when you need nested, semi-structured output. And Delta, which writes Parquet underneath but adds a transaction log, giving you atomic writes, updates, and time travel. When in doubt, write Parquet or Delta.

Next, and this is the one that can quietly destroy data, mode. Mode decides what Spark does when the target location already has data in it. Overwrite replaces whatever was there, so be careful, this is how people accidentally wipe a table. Append adds your new rows alongside the existing ones, which is what you want for daily loads. Error, the default, refuses to write and throws if the target exists, a safety net so you don't clobber anything by accident. And ignore silently does nothing if the target already exists. Always know which mode you're in before you run a write to a real location.

Then there's layout, how the output is physically organized on disk, and getting this right is what makes future reads fast. Partition by splits your data into separate folders based on a column's value, say one folder per date. Then when someone later filters on that column, Spark skips entire folders instead of scanning everything. That's called partition pruning, and it's one of the biggest performance wins available. Bucket by, used when you save as a table, hashes rows into a fixed number of buckets, which makes later joins and aggregations on that key cheaper because the data is pre-grouped. And sort by orders the data within each bucket, often paired with bucketing. Good layout is an investment, you pay a little at write time and save a lot on every read after.

Now the sinks, the methods that actually pull the trigger and write. Save writes to a path on a filesystem or object store, plain files. Save as table registers the result as a managed table in the catalog, so others can query it by name. Jdbc writes rows out to a relational database. And insert into appends into an existing table, matching by column position. These are the verbs that turn your configured write into real bytes on disk.

And finally, where all of this lands, the output. Save produces files in your storage. Save as table creates or fills a Hive table in the metastore. Jdbc lands rows in a database, your JDBC target. And writing in Delta format produces a Delta table, with its full transaction history. Notice how the sink method you choose lines up with the destination you get.

So the whole write path funnels together. You pick a format to encode the data, a mode to say what happens if the target exists, and a layout to organize it for fast future reads. All three feed into the sink method you call, and that produces your output. The two things to burn into memory are these. Mode overwrite is a loaded gun, so always confirm it's what you mean. And partition by is your single best lever for fast downstream reads, so think about how your data will be queried before you write it. Read carefully, write deliberately, and the rest of the pipeline takes care of itself.
